g a' b'framework for its fullest expression."' b'' b'"(3) they reaffirm that democracy is an inherent element of' b'the rule of law. they recognize the importance of pluralism' b'with regard to political organizations."' b'' b'"(4) they confirm that they will respect each other\'s right' b'freely to choose and develop, in accordance with' b'international human rights standards, their political, social,' b'economic and cultural systems. in exercising this right, they' b'will ensure that their laws, regulations, practices, and policies' b'conform with their obligations under international law and' b'are brought into harmony with the provisions of the' b'declaration on principles and other csce commitments."' b'' b'"(5) they solemnly declare that among those elements of' b'justice which are essential to the full expression of the' b'inherent dignity and of the equal and inalienable rights of all' b'human beings are the following. b'' b'". a clear separation between the state and political' b'parties; in particular, political parties will not be merged with' b'the state. b'' b'". to ensure that the will of the people serves as' b'the basis of the authority of government, the participating' b'states will. b'' b'"(7.4) ensure that (votes) are counted and reported' b'honestly with the official results made public;"' b'' b'"(7.5) respect the right of citizens to seek political or public' b'office, individually or as representatives of political parties or' b'organizations, without discrimination."' b'' b'' b' relevant sections of the' b' international covenant of october b' referenced above' b'' b'the states parties to the present covenant. recognizing' b'that. the ideal of free human beings enjoying civil and' b'political freedom and freedom from fear and want can only' b'be achieved if conditions are created whereby everyone may' b'enjoy his civil and political rights, as well as his economic,' b'social, and cultural rights, considering the obligation of' b'states under the charter of the united nations to promote' b'universal respect for, and observance of, human rights and' b'freedoms. agree upon the following articles. b'' b'article each state party to the present covenant' b'undertakes to respect and to ensure to all individuals within' b'its territory and subject to its jurisdiction the rights' b'recognized in the present covenant, without distinction of' b'any kind, such as race, colour, sex, language, religion,' b'political or other opinion, national or social origin, property,' b'birth, or other status.' b'' b'(2) where not already provided for by existing legislative or' b'other measures, each state party to the present covenant' b'undertakes to take the necessary steps, in accordance with its' b'constitutional processes and with the provisions of the' b'present covenant, to adopt such legislative or other measures' b'as may be necessary to give effect to the rights recognized in' b'the present covenant. b'' b'article the states parties to the present covenant' b'undertake to ensure the equal right of men and women to' b'the enjoyment of all civil and political rights set forth in the' b'present covenant. b'' b'article every citizen shall have the right and the' b'opportunity, without any of the distinctions mentioned in' b'article and without unreasonable restrictions: (a) to take' b'part in the conduct of public affairs, directly or through' b'freely chosen representatives; (b) to vote and to be elected at' b'genuine periodic elections which shall be by universal and' b'equal suffrage and shall be held by secret ballot,' b'guaranteeing the free expression of the will of the electors; (c)' b'to have access, on general terms of equality, to public service' b'in his country.' b'' b'article all persons are equal before the law and are' b'entitled without any discrimination to the equal protection of' b'the law. in this respect, the law shall prohibit any' b'discrimination and guarantee to all persons equal and' b'effective protection against discrimination on any ground' b'such as race, colour, sex, language, religion, political or other' b'opinion, national or social origin, property, birth, or other' b'status.' b'' b'' b'' b'-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-' b'there will be no peace without freedom.' b'think globally act locally.' b'resist much. obey little.' b'question authority.' b'' b'comments from bob waldrop are the responsibility of bob' b'waldrop! for a good time call b'' b'snail mail: p.o. box b' salt lake city, utah b' united states of america' b'voice phone: b'-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-' b'' b'' b'' b'--' b"\t\t don't blame me; i voted libertarian." b'disclaimer: i speak for myself, except as noted; copyright rich thomson' b'uucp: ...!uunet!dsd.es.com!rthomson\t\t\trich thomson' b'============================================================================' b'' b'when the words fold open,' b'it means the death of doors;' b'even casement windows sense the danger. (amon liner)' 